Done
I guess this property should be part of different interface , which will be implemented by system level object.
yeah since this interface modified to implement at user level. I removed Enabled property from this interface, will add new separate interface to have GoogleAuthenticator Enabled property
Done
Why would it be "NotAllowed"?
When MFA disable and user tries to execute this method, then NotAllowed error will be used.
Why?  Shouldn't you be able to create a secret key before you enable the MFA?  Otherwise you can get yourself into a state where you enabled MFA but haven't set the secret key, right?

SecretKey at the user's home directory will indicate the PAM module to look for TOTP to authenticate. So unless MFA is enabled for the system, CreateSecretKey is not relevant. 
When MFA is enabled and secret key is not set, the login attempt will get a response (a redfish message registry) saying the MFA is enabled and secret key is not set for this user. This will take the user through the registration process which starts with CreateSecretKey.

yeah User is not allowed to create secret key before enabling MFA
User allowed to create secret key after MFA enabled.
During redfish session create with MFA enabled user and no secret key setup then redfish session gets created with ConfigureSelf authority(limited config privilege) and user will be asked to generate secret by using GenerateSecretKeyRequired message registry similar to passwordChangeRequired configuration.

> yeah User is not allowed to create secret key before enabling MFA
> User allowed to create secret key after MFA enabled.

But why?  Does this impose some security vulnerability?  I'm not understanding why you can't create a key first.  I could enable, create a key, and then disable and the key is still there, right?

I dont see any use-case to support secret key before enabling MFA and if user randomly generate secret key and later when enable MFA and then user will be locked out.

implementation may check mfa enabled and secret key setup then user will be allowed to generate secret key.

I have captured generate secret flow with mfa in this design doc
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/docs/+/73054/13/designs/google-authenticator-mfa.md#227
correction: implementation may check mfa enabled and secret key is not setup then user will be allowed to generate secret key.

Are you going to clear the secret key when MFA is disabled?  It doesn't really seem any different.

I understand the flow as documented.  That flow doesn't seem to preclude someone from separately setting up a secret key, at least not at a DBus level, so I'm trying to understand why we're going out of our way to write _more_ code.  it just doesn't make sense to me.

I'm not convinced we should be enforcing a particular Redfish policy with a DBus implementation.  My view is you're trying to replicate Redfish policy, property names, etc. directly into DBus.

ok, since we are going to implement redfish spec, i am trying to make sure D-bus interface have all necessary properties and errors..

anyways i removed this NotAllowed error, will discuss more during implementations and add it back if its required.
Done
What are the conditions where this method would be unavailable??

D-bus implementation invokes google-authenticator to create secret key,
if this google-authenticator binary is not available as part of build then CreateSecretKey method returns Unavailable error

Why would the interface exist if all the required elements to support it are not installed?  Don't push this back onto the dbus client; there is no reason they would care and you're making extra code for them.

+1
If the secret key generation fails for any reason, it can return just a internal failure.
Ok
Please don't add new InternalFailure.
when there is a unexpected firmware error, which error needs to be returned?

Hi sunitha 
as per this discussion, InternalFailure removed
OK. Any reason for not sending out InternalFailure Patrick?

The reason for not using InternalFailure is that your client can't do anything about it.  They've called a dbus interface, you gave them that, and then what?

If your process is in a bad state, I'd rather you crash so we can collect a coredump and debug the bad state and at least then systemd will restart your process.  Just telling your dbus client "something went wrong" makes everyone confused and gives us no data.
Done
Please don't add new InternalFailures.
done

nitpick, can we call this

SecretKeyIsValid
Done

please rephrase. The word 'whether' duplicated
"This property indicates whether google authenticator secret key is generated for the given user"
Done

Do we have examples of what another MFA protocol would need for a dbus interface?  I'm not super keen on this being a one-off `GoogleAuthenticator` interface.  What would a `MicrosoftAuthenticator` interface look like?  Can we just make this a `MFAAuthenticator` interface and use paths or enums to model which one is enabled?

GoogleAuthenticator or MicrosoftAuthenticator is nothing but TOTP authenticators.
redfish supports both of them, it make sense to use common name, will use generic name "TOTPAuthenticator"

This seems like a really odd interface to return.  The secret key file itself is an implementation detail, and really all we should be returning is "file has been created successfully", right?

If we DO need to return it, in terms of size, shouldn't we just be returning this as a string/byte array (depending on if it's binary or not)?  I didn't think these secret keys were all that big.
secret key is not a big string, but I think sending secret key as a string on D-bus will be security concern, similarly password string was never sent over D-bus.
Is it necessary to return for any reason?  Maybe we need to document that reason.
yeah its necessary to share secretkey with bmcweb so that bmcweb can populate secret key in redfish response

if bmcweb is sending the secret to the user off box, we’ve defeated any sort of security around nefarious processes sniffing the secret.

this secret is also only shared once at setup time, so it doesn’t have the same requirements as passwords, which might be sent many times.

let’s do this as a simple return (not an fd) and treat changing it to an fd as something we can document and change once things are working.

yeah secret key is shared only once during secret key setup.

are you suggesting to change return secret key as  string?
if its not a security concern, i am ok to change to string type
Ack, I have modified to string type.
Yes, change to string (assuming it's text and small).
Do we need dbus paths defined here in order to allow a dbus-client to differentiate between Google and Microsoft TOTP implementation endpoints?
I think we dont need now since we dont have plans to implement, even though redfish supports Microsoft TOTP but Microsoft implementation is not open source.

Is this interface generic enough to support multiple OTP types?  I suspect if we're limiting to Google authenticator for the moment, this interface seems fine, and we can just define that this will exist on the same path as the multi factor config.  If this is truly generic, in the future we can differentiate.
yes, this generic interface for TOTP auth types. lets modify in future as needed.

SecurID for example teaks a Server URI, ClientId, and ClientSecret as configuration parameters.  Clearly this interface doesn't fulfill that?  What am I missing.

Google and Microsoft authenticator take the same parameters as whats here, so maybe we call this out as only for those two?

yes, Google/Microsoft authenticator are TOTP based auth mechanisms.
secureID and clientCert are different authentication mechanisms
This TOTPAuthenticator interface is generic for TOTP based auth mechanism.

You have two options here:
1. Call out that this exists on the primary user config path and say it applies to whichever setting is enabled (MSFT or Google).
2. Do what Patrick asked for and call out specific path names for each setting type so we can have separate settings for every mode.


I figured 1 was easier for you, but if you really want to do 2, you need to actually implement it in the patchset and add dbus paths.
I choose option 1 here
I don't see any mention of Google or MSFT in the description if that's the case
Done
doesn't it require string argument?
Done
